    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm working on an embedded project for an automotive control unit and we're seeing a slow RAM exhaustion over about 4-6 hours of continuous operation. i've looked at the main loop and can't see any obvious missing deletes, but it's definitely leaking something. can you give me a systematic approach for finding where the leak is happening in a C++ environment like this?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A systematic approach for finding memory leaks in an embedded C++ environment is crucial, especially when you're dealing with a slow bleed like this. You can start by using a memory profiling tool, though these can be tricky on constrained embedded systems, perhaps requiring a dedicated debugging probe or logging approach. If you can't run a full profiler, instrument your code with custom memory tracking functions—wrap `new` and `delete` (or `malloc`/`free`) to count allocations and track the call stack at the point of allocation. This allows you to pinpoint which function is responsible for the growing memory footprint. Remember, even small, persistent leaks in a tight loop can accumulate into a significant problem over several hours.",
