    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "instrumenting might be tough because of the timing constraints on this hardware. we can't really afford much overhead. do you have any suggestions for how to narrow it down manually without a heavy profiler? like, how do i actually differentiate between legitimate long-term heap usage and a leak that's just slowly creeping up?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If overhead is a major concern, you need to treat this like a targeted hunt for a specific, persistent pattern, rather than a broad sweep. First, establish a baseline: run the system for a short, controlled period (say, 15 minutes) and record the RAM usage. Then, let it run for a longer period (say, 4 hours) and record the usage again, noting the delta. If the delta is consistently increasing, you have a leak, not just legitimate usage.\n\nTo narrow it down manually, focus on dynamic data structures and resource acquisition within your main loop or interrupt handlers. Are you using `std::vector` or custom dynamic arrays? If so, check every single place where an object is added to these containers; ensure that when the object is no longer needed, the container is either cleared or the object is explicitly destroyed and removed. A common pitfall is holding onto pointers to dynamically allocated objects that are never properly released when the context changes.",
      "source": "target",
